column20: 2014 brood year was the first year to be tagged; therefore, the first full return cohort would be 2019. Brood are dip-netted from a hatchery outflow pipe from the river and, where possible, clipped fish are not included in brood. There pHOS estimate is biased high due to the removals being collected from a hatchery outflow pipe and is not  a true representation of the river spawners. pNOB is adjusted based on the mark rate of  of fish kept for brood, i.e. expanded.

column36: No assessment of river done. pHOS cannot equal 1 minus pNOB because natural origin brood is preferentially selected for and therefore biases the sample. Snootli and Atnarko stray into this population.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column11: BC East Vancouver Island Ocean Fall (EVI + SFj)
column19: The population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pNOB, the proportion of natural origin spawners in the hatchery broodstock, because only hatchery brood stock is sampled. column36: Brood is collected from swim-ins at Quinsam. pNOB value presented is 1 minus pHOS and represents the natural origin spawners. pHOS is from dead pitch sampling on the Campbell. All CWTs are likely Quinsam fish as Campbell chinook are not CWT'd.  Campbell River chinook are only thermally marked.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column36: Expand the visual mark rate using the ratio of CWT in the total release. VMR = visual mark rate, Rcwt = Ratio of CWT in total release pHOS = VMR/Rcwt   where Rcwt equals the ratio of CWTs in the total release. For Phillips this averaged 0.94 for brood years 2011-2016

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column36: Expand the visual mark rate using the ratio of CWT in the total release. VMR = visual mark rate, Rcwt = Ratio of CWT in total release pHOS = VMR/Rcwt   where Rcwt equals the ratio of CWTs in the total release. For Phillips this averaged 0.94 for brood years 2011-2016

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.
column26: No estimate of survival or production possible (e.g. population is not marked, neither brood stock nor river are sampled.and there is no appropriate biostandard indicator). column11: BC East Vancouver Island Ocean Fall (EVI + SFj)
column19: The population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pNOB, the proportion of natural origin spawners in the hatchery broodstock, because only hatchery brood stock is sampled. Or, the population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pHOS, the proportion of hatchery origin spawners in the natural spawning population. In the former, pHOS = 1 minus pNOB, and in the latter, pNOB = 1 minus pHOS.
column20: Only pHOS estimate available. pNOB was assumed to be equal to 1 minus pHOS.

column36: Brood is collected from swim-ins at Quinsam. pNOB value presented is 1 minus pHOS and represents the natural origin spawners. pHOS is from dead pitch sampling on the Campbell. All CWTs are likely Quinsam fish as Campbell chinook are not CWT'd.  Campbell River chinook are only thermally marked.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.
column26: No estimate of survival or production possible (e.g. population is not marked, neither brood stock nor river are sampled.and there is no appropriate biostandard indicator).  In this instance the PNI cannot be calculated and the program must be scaled to an appropriately low level of production or assumed to be high risk.

column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: Direct estimates of both pHOS and pNOB are available.  Population is marked (Coded Wire Tags, adipose clips, otolith, or Parental Based Tags) and both river and brood stock are sampled.  Standard statistical assumptions and methodologies with respect to the marking method apply.
column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

column20: 2014 brood year was the first year to be tagged; therefore, the first full return cohort would be 2019. column11: BC Southern Mainland - Boundary Bay Ocean Fall
column19: No estimate of survival or production possible (e.g. population is not marked, neither brood stock nor river are sampled.and there is no appropriate biostandard indicator). column20: This stock is not CWT'd. The estimates were populated in the CWT cells out of convenience. The hatchery fish had alternating ventral clips by brood year up to and including the 2015 brood year. Adipose clipped fish found in this river are assumed to be Green River stock from the US as no adipose clipped fish are applied to Boundary Bay chinook. All fish are trapped at the fence and are checked for marks and counted through. The only times that fish are missed is during high water events and chinook can possibly swim over the fence. Adipose clipped fish are not used for brood as they are assumed to be Green River. 2010 was the first year that adipose fin clipped fish showed up in the LCR. pNOB was estimated as the total of non clipped fish divided by the sum of non clipped fish and pelvic fin clipped fish. For 2010 onward, pHOS was calculated the total number of marked fish (adipose clipped and pelvic clipped) divided by the total escapement. Fish are selected for brood randomly (ventral clips and non clipped fish) except for making a point to collect jacks representative of the entire population by percentage. The random sampling description was provided by Bob Schaefer (Community Advisor, DFO). For our purposes, this was also assumed to be the case historically.

Or, the population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pHOS, the proportion of hatchery origin spawners in the natural spawning population. In the former, pHOS = 1 minus pNOB, and in the latter, pNOB = 1 minus pHOS.
column26: No estimate of survival or production possible (e.g. population is not marked, neither brood stock nor river are sampled.and there is no appropriate biostandard indicator). column26: The population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pNOB, the proportion of natural origin spawners in the hatchery broodstock, because only hatchery brood stock is sampled. Or, the population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pHOS, the proportion of hatchery origin spawners in the natural spawning population. In the former, pHOS = 1 minus pNOB, and in the latter, pNOB = 1 minus pHOS.

Only the females had adipose fin clip observations recorded. 6 of the 13 females had adipose fin clips/CWTs. This mark rate assumes that female mark rates applies to the males and that all fish recorded were used for brood. Therefore, pNOB would be equal to 1 minus pHOS. Assuming all samples in biodata were used for brood stock. Adipose clip status was recorded for 13 females only, so assume 18 males were not checked.

column36: In 2015 there was no BSR submitted by Tofino. Brood used (10 males and 10 females) was estimated from reported eggs taken, and assuming 1:1 spawning. No sampling of brood was reported. 2015 was the big straying year. pHOS was then estimated to be 188/432 and pNOB was equal to 1 minus pHOS.

column27: Thermal mark data is only available for fish collected for brood only. The brood is collected and held at the hatchery until after DNA results are obtained. Non-Nahmint fish are culled and only Nahmint fish are used for brood. pNOB represents the proportion of fish that were actually spawned that were natural Nahmnint origin (based on DNA results). The pHOS estimate is based on thermal mark data from fish collected for brood and it is assumed that the fish collected for brood represent the natural spawners even though brood are collected far down in the system.

column27: Thermal mark data is only available for fish collected for brood only. The brood is collected and held at the hatchery until after DNA results are obtained. Non-Nahmint fish are culled and only Nahmint fish are used for brood. pNOB represents the proportion of fish that were actually spawned that were natural Nahmnint origin (based on DNA results). The pHOS estimate is based on thermal mark data from fish collected for brood and it is assumed that the fish collected for brood represent the natural spawners even though brood are collected far down in the system.

column27: Thermal mark data is only available for fish collected for brood only. The brood is collected and held at the hatchery until after DNA results are obtained. Non-Nahmint fish are culled and only Nahmint fish are used for brood. pNOB represents the proportion of fish that were actually spawned that were natural Nahmnint origin (based on DNA results). The pHOS estimate is based on thermal mark data from fish collected for brood and it is assumed that the fish collected for brood represent the natural spawners even though brood are collected far down in the system.

column26: The population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pNOB, the proportion of natural origin spawners in the hatchery broodstock, because only hatchery brood stock is sampled. Or, the population is marked but there is a direct estimate of only pHOS, the proportion of hatchery origin spawners in the natural spawning population. In the former, pHOS = 1 minus pNOB, and in the latter, pNOB = 1 minus pHOS.
column27: Thermally marked. Otolith samples from Conuma are from fish taken from the river, so there is only one stratum, and pHOS = pHOB, for all the Conuma hatchery stocks. There are no swim ins, and the mark rate in brood is assumed to be the same as the rest of the river
